    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec5">
      <title>Splitting TCGA-BRCA by sample source site</title>
      <p>TCGA is a multi-center project and tumor samples of TCGA-BRCA datasets were collected at 37 different clinical centers, which can result in some between-center variability. Therefore, we also evaluated <italic>Flimma</italic> and its baselines on a more realistic scenario, where TCGA-BRCA dataset was split according to the sample source sites, but we kept only 14 of the 37 cohorts, such that each cohort contained at least 3 samples of LumA and basal subtype.</p>
      <p>We selected 3, 5, 7, 10, and 14 cohorts such that subtype frequencies, mean stage, and age are dissimilar across the selected cohorts (cf. Additional file <xref rid="MOESM5" ref-type="media">5</xref>: Table S4 for details). We also added additional terms in linear models to account for possible cohort effects. Similar to the previous experiments, <italic>Flimma</italic> clearly outperforms all meta-analysis approaches in terms of RMSE, precision, and recall (Table <xref rid="Tab5" ref-type="table">5</xref> and Additional file <xref rid="MOESM6" ref-type="media">6</xref>: Table S5).
